	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>rainwarrior</b> [ Mon Apr 21, 2014 10:07 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I'm a big fan of AxROM/BxROM:<br /><br />Advantages:<br />- very simple hardware (a single 4 bit latch chip)<br />- 32k bank size makes it easy to organize/pack data<br />- well suited to divide the banks by data function (level bank, chr bank, music bank, gameplay bank, etc.)<br />- CHR-RAM allows a lot of flexibility for CHR storage<br /><br />Disadvantages:<br />- poorly suited for DPCM (need to duplicate it in all banks used during playback)<br />- some amount of code duplication required<br />- no IRQ for advanced timing effects<br />- no CHR-ROM for page flipping animation

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>MottZilla</b> [ Mon Apr 21, 2014 12:08 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />New boards using a MMC3 (mapper 4) clone are available. If you don't need anything that sophisticated there are the UxROM (mapper 2) as well as a similar one used by &quot;Holy Diver&quot; which gives you UxROM-like PRG banking, CNROM style CHR banking, and Horizontal/Vertical mirroring switching. <br /><br />UxROM is pretty good for something more advanced than NROM but doesn't require CHR-ROM banking or SRAM backup. Ofcourse you can always create your own mapper to suit your needs.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Mon Apr 21, 2014 1:14 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The MMC5 is still a bit of a mystery, and AFAIK it hasn't been fully replicated yet. Support for it in popular Flash Carts (PowerPak and Everdrive N8) is partial. It would also be significantly more expensive to include in production carts than AxROM or UxROM for example, since an FPGA that can host the MMC5 costs tens of dollar (I think) while the simple logic chips for the discrete mappers cost dimes.<br /><br />Over the years I've grown fond of the simplest discrete logic mappers. They don't give you anything more than access to more PRG-ROM, but in most cases that's all you'll need. With CHR-RAM you can pull off a lot of interesting tricks, and by dynamically updating parts of it (a rudimentary form of simulating CHR bankswitching) you can show very diverse graphics throughout each level.<br /><br />Sure, scanline counters, 8KB of extra RAM and fine CHR bankswitching all sound like awesome features to have available, but the difficulty and cost they add to producing carts is hardly worth it, IMO.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">MottZilla wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">you can always create your own mapper to suit your needs.</div><br />But you'll also have to make your own emulator or modify an existing one to support your new mapper, otherwise you won't be able to test your ROM. You'll also need to understand at least the very basics of electronics in order to design something feasible.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Mon Apr 21, 2014 4:26 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It would also be significantly more expensive to include in production carts than AxROM or UxROM for example, since an FPGA that can host the MMC5 costs tens of dollar (I think) while the simple logic chips for the discrete mappers cost dimes.<br /></div>I'm pretty certain we could build a modern MMC5 clone for about $10 of parts. Which, yes, is about 100× more expensive than AxROM, or 50× more expensive than UxROM, and 40× more expensive than mapper 70 (UxROM PRG + sixteen 8KiB CHR banks).<br /><br />128KiB of CHR-RAM on Color Dreams/mapper 70/oversize GNROM board are my current favorite discrete logic mappers, because apparently any new RAMs or ROMs smaller than 128KiB are basically the same cost as the 128KiB one. So you may as well take advantage of it...<br /><br />Looking around, I see a public quote for AX5202P of around 20CNY, or about 3.5$. (I also see some people offering much lower prices, which I don't know if I trust)<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">fine CHR bankswitching<br /></div>Doesn't quite count as &quot;fine&quot;, but NINA-001 is nice for providing MMC1/VRC1-style 4KiB CHR banks (so that you don't have to couple your sprites tilset to your background tileset), but it officially only supports 64KiB PRG.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">But you'll also have to make your own emulator or modify an existing one to support your new mapper, otherwise you won't be able to test your ROM. You'll also need to understand at least the very basics of electronics in order to design something feasible.<br /></div>One of the biggest complicating things about the MMC5 is that it provides so much versatility when any given game will most likely only use one of them. (four different PRG banking modes? six different CHR banking modes? all the things the extra 1KiB RAM can be used for? ) Which is why I've personally been recommending &quot;(talk to people to help you) pick a subset of the MMC5 if you want something that the MMC3 doesn't provide&quot;, because it gets the cart out from under the horse.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tokumaru</b> [ Mon Apr 21, 2014 5:19 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">One of the biggest complicating things about the MMC5 is that it provides so much versatility when any given game will most likely only use one of them. (four different PRG banking modes? six different CHR banking modes? all the things the extra 1KiB RAM can be used for? ) Which is why I've personally been recommending &quot;(talk to people to help you) pick a subset of the MMC5 if you want something that the MMC3 doesn't provide&quot;, because it gets the cart out from under the horse.</div><br />That's good advice, but things are complicated when you have to depend on someone else for periods as long as the development cycle of a (big) game.<br /><br />Say you're looking the mapper you'll use in the game you plan to release on actual carts. You will not begin programming for a mapper until you find someone who is willing to supply the physical mapper, but once you do find a supplier, it will be a while until the game is ready to be put on cartridges, and in the mean time something can go wrong (the supplier abandons the community or whatever), and you're screwed. Restricting yourself to the simple mappers ensures that the cartridges will be easy to manufacture when the time comes, no matter who does it.<br /><br />This is the reason I prefer to stick to simple mappers. I can't make any commitment to have the software ready by a certain date, and I don't want to risk not being able to manufacture cartridges when I do finish the software. The only way I'd use a complex mapper was if I had a significant number of boards with me since the beginning of development, or if I had the hardware knowledge to produce the mapper myself, so I wouldn't have to depend on anyone else.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


