	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: About mappers and homebrew</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />AxROM and BxROM use 32KB bank switching though, so you may not like that. I prefer the UxROM model with the lower 16K banking and the upper 16K fixed. AxROM you're stuck with 1 screen mirroring as well, which depending again on what kind of game and how you like to program may or may not bother you. <br /><br />But to give some examples of games that used just discrete mappers like UxROM.<br />1943<br />Castlevania<br />Commando<br />Contra<br />Duck Tales 1&amp;2<br />Ghosts 'n Goblins<br />Goonies II<br />Guardian Legend<br />Gun.Smoke<br />Jackal<br />Lifeforce<br />Mega Man<br />Metal Gear<br />Paperboy 2<br />Rush 'n Attack<br />Rygar<br />Section Z<br />Side Pocket<br />Skate or Die!<br />Top Gun<br />Trog!<br />Trojan<br />Uncanny X-Men<br /><br />Hopefully you're familiar with some of those. They span many different kinds of games but they all use the very simple setup of UxROM. All it provides is that 16K/16K split and access up to 128K or 256K of PRG-ROM with fixed 8K CHR-RAM. And again it's not hard to add some extras to UxROM if you decide you need it. You can easily go up to 512K of PRG-ROM, or add mirroring control if your game needs it to scroll a level Vertically sometimes and Horizontally other times. It's well known how to add 8K of battery backed PRG-RAM if you want your game to save data like for a RPG. If you decide you want to do any advanced CHR banking you'll probably be beyond regular UxROM into something custom. <br /><br />I do agree with tokumaru that it's not a bad idea to stick with mappers you can be absolutely sure you can build carts for. Anything using all discrete parts you certainly can. But I do think that INL's new boards should be very available for awhile so MMC3 is certainly an option.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
